abcock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): although the first element of this name would suggest it is derived from the Middle English personal name <i>Babb</i> (see   Babb  ), apparently it is a post-medieval form of <b>Badcock</b>, from the Middle English personal name <i>Badecok</i>, a pet form of <i>Bade</i> (see   Bade  ) + the diminutive suffix <i>-cok</i>. There is no reason why a Middle English <i>Babbecok</i>, a pet form of <i>Babb</i> (itself a pet form of   Barbara  ), should not have existed, but evidence has yet to be found.","History: James Babcock settled in Portsmouth, RI, in 1642."],"variants":[{"name":"Babb","meanings":["English (Devon, Somerset, and Cornwall): from the Middle English personal name <i>Babb(e)</i>, usually no doubt a pet form of the female personal name <i>Barbara</i> (see   Barbara  ), but possibly in some cases a survival of the Old English personal name <i>Babba</i>, which is found in several placenames, including Babbacombe in Devon and Babington in Somerset.","English (Devon, Somerset, and Cornwall): from Middle English <i>babe</i> ‘infant, young child’, applied as a nickname.","Americanized form of German   Bobb   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":2,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":47,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Babcock was born in 1335, in Oxford, Oxfordshire, England. He married Babcock Lady Robert x."},"et":{"1335–":"1335–Surnud","1339–Female":"1339–Surnud","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1440":"1440","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England"},"fi":{"1335–":"1335–Kuollut","1339–Female":"1339–Kuollut","1340–Female":"1340–Kuollut","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1335–Male":"1335–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1440":"1440","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England"},"fr":{"1335–":"1335–Décédé","1339–Female":"1339–Décédée","1340–Female":"1340–Décédée","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1335–Male":"1335–Décédé","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1440":"14